Sure, here is a sample code for creating a Line Chart using Chart.js library for temperature vs pressure:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Line Chart - Temperature vs Pressure</title>
	<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
	<div style="width: 80%">
		<canvas id="myChart"></canvas>
	</div>

	<script>
		var ctx = document.getElementById('myChart').getContext('2d');
		var myChart = new Chart(ctx, {
			type: 'line',
			data: {
				labels: ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June'],
				datasets: [{
					label: 'Temperature (°C)',
					data: [15, 18, 20, 23, 26, 29],
					borderColor: 'rgba(255, 99, 132, 1)',
					borderWidth: 2,
					fill: false
				}, {
					label: 'Pressure (hPa)',
					data: [1013, 1011, 1010, 1009, 1008, 1007],
					borderColor: 'rgba(54, 162, 235, 1)',
					borderWidth: 2,
					fill: false
				}]
			},
			options: {
				scales: {
					yAxes: [{
						ticks: {
							beginAtZero: true
						}
					}]
				}
			}
		});
	</script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a Line Chart with two datasets: Temperature (in degrees Celsius) and Pressure (in hectopascals). The chart displays the data for the months of January through June. The y-axis is scaled to begin at zero. You can customize the labels and data to fit your needs.

